{"source_key":"sha256-77a8d0a023ee41ad7912180250238aff","record_index":2320,"record_hash":"sha256:3408e42feb6e9fbf5fd0ba9502e27cc12c9be6a1ee144094fbaef57e0a4476c3","timestamp":"2026-05-20T17:59:29.125Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Because they were the least justified expensive part.\n\nThey added three costs:\n\n- **Runtime cost:** every capture could diff up to 100 commits per branch just to store changed file lists.\n- **Storage cost:** those file lists can get big fast, especially in generated/vendor/lockfile-heavy commits.\n- **Maintenance cost:** they created a whole mini model: `CommitSnapshot`, caps, truncation, file counts, commit diff error handling, tests.\n\nAnd right now, the primitive layer does not use them. The useful v1 relationship primitive is `observed_targets`: branch/review/change keys. `find_related_sessions` verifies against that, not commit files.\n\nSo the cut is: keep worktree paths for handoff context, keep branch/review/change observations for lookup, but don’t eagerly persist per-commit file evidence before a review/handoff product actually needs it.\n\nIf later the review service wants file-overlap scoring, it can derive commit/path evidence at read time or in a feature-specific projection layer. That keeps `but-agentlog` smaller and avoids baking product scoring assumptions into durable metadata.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T17:59:29.125Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}